{"add":{"doc":{"id":"832601f8750edf6abc7a6e08339f7d12a6de4dd207073652715711290a1d0500","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/U2_Gelsenkirchen_August_3rd_2009.png/250px-U2_Gelsenkirchen_August_3rd_2009.png","previous":[],"after":["Since their inception, U2 have developed and maintained a distinctly recognisable sound, with emphasis on melodic instrumentals and expressive, larger-than-life vocals.[160] This approach is rooted partly in the early influence of record producer Steve Lillywhite at a time when the band was not known for musical proficiency.[161] The Edge has consistently used a rhythmic echo and a signature delay[162] to craft his distinctive guitar work, coupled with an Irish-influenced drone played against his syncopated melodies[163] that ultimately yields a well-defined ambient, chiming sound. Bono has nurtured his falsetto operatic voice[164] and has exhibited a notable lyrical bent towards social, political, and personal subject matter while maintaining a grandiose scale in his songwriting. In addition, The Edge has described U2 as a fundamentally live band.[163]"]}}}